Causal Inference Working Group: Electric Company Case Study

Adam Peterson

9/16/2020

Libraries

library(tidyverse)
library(equatiomatic)
library(rstanarm)
theme_set(theme_bw() + theme(strip.background=element_blank()))

Data

df <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/avehtari/ROS-Examples/master/ElectricCompany/data/electric.csv") %>% 
  mutate(treatment=factor(treatment,labels=c("Control","Treatment")),
         grade = factor(grade)) %>% select(-X1)
knitr::kable(head(df))
post_test pre_test grade treatment supp pair_id
48.9 13.8 1 Treatment 1 1
70.5 16.5 1 Treatment 0 2
89.7 18.5 1 Treatment 1 3
44.2 8.8 1 Treatment 0 4
77.5 15.3 1 Treatment 1 5
84.7 15.0 1 Treatment 0 6
  • post_test: Outcome variable, the post treatment reading test score
  • pre_test : Possible covariate, test taken prior to treatment
  • grade : Classroom’s grade level
  • treatment : Binary indicator variable where 1 denotes the classroom watched the tv show and 0 indicates they did not.
  • supp : Whether or not the class received supplemental treatment, NOTE: only available for 96 classes.
  • pair_id : Denotes which class’ are in which pairs

Checking for Imbalance, Overlap

Model Estimating Treatment-Grade Main and Interaction Effects

\[ \begin{aligned} \operatorname{post\_test} &= \alpha + \beta_{1}(\operatorname{treatment}_{\operatorname{Treatment}}) + \beta_{2}(\operatorname{grade}_{\operatorname{2}}) + \beta_{3}(\operatorname{grade}_{\operatorname{3}})\ + \\ &\quad \beta_{4}(\operatorname{grade}_{\operatorname{4}}) + \beta_{5}(\operatorname{treatment}_{\operatorname{Treatment}} \times \operatorname{grade}_{\operatorname{2}}) + \beta_{6}(\operatorname{treatment}_{\operatorname{Treatment}} \times \operatorname{grade}_{\operatorname{3}}) + \beta_{7}(\operatorname{treatment}_{\operatorname{Treatment}} \times \operatorname{grade}_{\operatorname{4}})\ + \\ &\quad \epsilon \end{aligned} \]

fit <- stan_glm(post_test ~ treatment*grade,
                data=df,
                prior_intercept=NULL,prior=NULL)
fit

Pre Treatment Predictors

Would including the pre_test covariate in the model help?

Model with Pre-Test Included

\[ \begin{aligned} \operatorname{post\_test} &= \alpha + \beta_{1}(\operatorname{treatment}_{\operatorname{Treatment}}) + \beta_{2}(\operatorname{grade}_{\operatorname{2}}) + \beta_{3}(\operatorname{grade}_{\operatorname{3}})\ + \\ &\quad \beta_{4}(\operatorname{grade}_{\operatorname{4}}) + \beta_{5}(\operatorname{pre\_test}) + \beta_{6}(\operatorname{treatment}_{\operatorname{Treatment}} \times \operatorname{grade}_{\operatorname{2}}) + \beta_{7}(\operatorname{treatment}_{\operatorname{Treatment}} \times \operatorname{grade}_{\operatorname{3}})\ + \\ &\quad \beta_{8}(\operatorname{treatment}_{\operatorname{Treatment}} \times \operatorname{grade}_{\operatorname{4}}) + \beta_{9}(\operatorname{grade}_{\operatorname{2}} \times \operatorname{pre\_test}) + \beta_{10}(\operatorname{grade}_{\operatorname{3}} \times \operatorname{pre\_test}) + \beta_{11}(\operatorname{grade}_{\operatorname{4}} \times \operatorname{pre\_test})\ + \\ &\quad \epsilon \end{aligned} \]

fit <- stan_glm(post_test ~ treatment*grade + pre_test*grade,
                data=df,
                prior_intercept=NULL,prior=NULL)
fit
